Chapter 1 of Data Camp - Intro to Time Series Analsys

Def: A time series is a sequence of data in chronological order

print() prints the data with time stamps and includes the start, end and frequency informatino.

plot() plots a time series with time on the horizontal axis.

The course will cover basic time series models

  • White Noise (WN)
  • Random Walk (RW)
  • Autoregression (AR)
  • Simple Moving Average (MA)

The plot() function knows about time series and will plot them appropriately. Here are some examples

par(mfrow=c(3, 1))

plot(Nile)
plot(Nile, 
     xlab = "Year", 
     ylab = "River Volume (1e9 m^{3})")

plot(Nile, 
     xlab="Year", 
     ylab="River Volumne (1e9 m^{3})", 
     main="Annual River Nile Volume at Aswan, 1871-1970",
     type='b')

The ts version of plot() provides for a y= value which will be used as the y axis values.

When plotting a Continuous time index the points will not be evenly spaced, they will be spaced based on the continuous value. To addresss this, you can create a discrete index.

cti = 1:20 + runif(20)
cts = c(rnorm(10), rnorm(10))
dti = 1:20

par(mfrow=c(2, 1))

plot(cti, cts, type='b')
plot(dti, cts, type='b')

Sampling Frequency

Time series data can be equally spaced, such as hourly temperature measurements, or unevently spaced such as the temperature every time you check e-mail. Time series can also have missing values. For example, stocks are not traded on weekends, so there will be missing daily data for Saturdays and Sundays as well as possible holidays.

There are some assumptions made about a time series.

  • Consecutive obs are equally spaced
  • The have a discrete-time observation index
  • This may hold approximately as in the case of stock trading with weekends and holidays missing.

4 Functions can be used to validate a time series.

  • start(), which will return the start values, i.e.1 1 may indicate it starts on hour 1 of day 1
  • end(), returns the end values. i.e.1 24 may indicate it ends on hour 24 of day 1
  • frequency() returns the frequency, how many observations. i.e.24
  • deltat() returns the time interval duration. i.e.0.0417 is 1/24 or hourly.
  • cycle() returns the position of an obs in the cycle of each obs.

Missing values.

Missingness is represented by NA in R. There are many ways to handle it and differnet functions in R handle it differently. Missing data can be removed or imputed (calculated) from the remaining data.

data("AirPassengers")
AirPassengers[seq((7*12)+1, length.out=12)] <- NA  # NA out 19576

par(mfrow=c(2, 1))
plot(AirPassengers)

AirPassengers[85:96] <- mean(AirPassengers, na.rm = TRUE)

plot(AirPassengers)

data("AirPassengers")
points(AirPassengers, type = "l", col = 2, lty = 3)

The ts class

To turn something into a time series use the ts() function.

data_vector = rnorm(50)

head(data_vector)
## [1]  0.2132799 -1.2874050 -0.2896775 -0.7212702 -1.4044961 -0.3049528
par(mfrow=c(2, 1))

plot(data_vector)

time_series = ts(data_vector, start=2004, frequency=4)   # start in 2004 with quarterly frequency

print(time_series)

Check if its a ts

is.ts() returns TRUE if an object is a ts and FALSE if not.

data("EuStockMarkets")

is.ts(EuStockMarkets)
## [1] TRUE
start(EuStockMarkets)
## [1] 1991  130
end(EuStockMarkets)
## [1] 1998  169
frequency(EuStockMarkets)
## [1] 260
plot(EuStockMarkets)

ts.plot(EuStockMarkets, col = 1:4, xlab = "Year", ylab = "Index Value", main = "Major European Stock Indices, 1991-1998")
legend("topleft", colnames(EuStockMarkets), lty = 1, col = 1:4, bty = "n")
